    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent. | Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>June 10<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. 79</date>
                    <salute>My dear Sulivan.</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
                    <p>The progress of the Fuegians is wonderful, &amp; had it not occurred would have been to me quite incredible. Many thanks for the magazine.—<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
                    <p>You have all been in a lamentable state &amp; I am very sorry to hear it; though you now seem all fairly well again.—<ref target="#foot.f2"/> I have not been very well of late &amp; my scientific work tires me more than it used to do; but I have nothing else to do, &amp; whether one is worn out a year or two sooner or later signifies but little. Farewell my old friend— I have had to answer an abominable number of letters, so will say no more, except to beg you to remember us very kindly to Lady Sulivan.<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>My dear Sulivan | Yours very truly | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">With his <ref target="./DCP-LETT-12097.xml">letter of 9 June 1879</ref>, Sulivan had sent CD a copy of the <hi rend="italic">South American Missionary Magazine</hi> that included an account of developments at the mission station in Ushuaia, Tierra del Fuego. </note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-12097.xml">letter from B. J. Sulivan, 9 June 1879</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">Sulivan’s wife was <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_6821.xml">Sophia Sulivan</ref>.</note>  
        </div>
    
